Main prisma PRS extraction and validation pipelines

prismaFuns.Rd

These functions comprises the main PRISMA workhorse as they perform all the steps required to extract a PRS potentially chatacterizing a phenotypic trait, given a set of samples, their genetic polymorphims and the phenotypes to participate in the subsequent GWAS associations in a GWASExperiment object. Out of these, the prisma function combines all three and performs:

  • Input checking and subsequent management according to the input details

  • Iterative calls to prsPipeline for each SNP effect estimation method and is the main prisma iterator for extracting multiple PRSs to be later combined.

  • Call to prsSelection which evaluates the output of prsPipeline and selects the best PRS candidates for each SNP effect estimation method.

  • Wrap up of the data to feed the later PRISMA report and basic evaluation graphics.

  • Output of an object containing all the results and input to the PRISMA reporting function.

prsPipeline is the iterator of the PRISMA workflow. It will produce a list of GWASExperiment objects or their summaries, up to the filling of the prsbetas slot of the GWASExperiment.

prsSelection accepts as input the output of prsPipeline and evaluate and select the best PRS candidates according to the input arguments.

prismaPipeline seves as a wrapper of prisma and makes sure that the pipeline will resume if crashed at any point as well as write checkpoints and create the report.

Arguments

gwe

A GWASExperiment object with GWA tests performed. In other words, gwa must have been applied.

dnList

A list resulting from a de novo PRS extraction pipeline. See also Details.

phenotype

The trait for which a PRS is sought to be extracted. It should be a character of length 1 and exist in the phenotypes of gwe.

covariates

The covariates to include in regression models. It should be a character vector of traits all existing in the phenotypes of gwe.

pcs

Inlcude PCs in the regression model? Defaults to FALSE.

npcs

The number of PCs to use if pcs=TRUE. If npcs=0, the PCs available in gwe will be used.

trainSize

The fraction of the training set used for summary statistics calculation in each iteration. See also Details. Defaults to 0.8.

niter

Number of PRS extraction iterations. Defaults to 100.

resolution

How to resolve the best number of SNPs in a PRS candidate, either by validating a PRS with as many SNPs as the number of appearances at each frequency cutoff (frequency, default) or as many SNPs as those included at different quantile cutoffs of the frequency of appearance distribution ("quantile"). See also Details.

step

The number of steps or step increment for resolution. Defaults to 1 for resolution="frequency" or a set of predefined quantiles when resolution="quantile". See also Details.

minFreq

The minimum accepted frequency of appearance of a SNP in niter iterations to be considered as member of a PRS candidate. Defaults to 2.

minSnps

The minimum number of SNPs included in a PRS candidate. Defaults to 5.

dropSameQuantiles

When resolution="quantile" drop quantiles with the same SNPs? Defaults to TRUE. See also Details.

aggregation

How should the SNPs from different PRS algorithms should be aggregated at the end of the iterations in order to create the distribution of appearances. One of "intersection" (default) or "union". See also Details.

effectWeight

How to summarize SNP effects (regression coefficients) across the niter iterations. One of "mean" (default), "mean" or "weight". See also Details.

prsSelectMethod

How to select the number of SNPs for the PRS after niter iterations. One of "maxima" (default) or "elbow". See also Details.

prsSelectCrit

One of "prs_r2" (default), "prs_pvalue" or "prs_aic". Determines what criterion is used for PRS selection. See also Details.

prsSelectStat

One of "mean" (default), "median" or "none". Determines which calculated statistic (mean, median) is used to summarize the prsSelectCrit in the evaluation metrics and when applicable (e.g. not applicable in p-values).

prsSelectR2

One of "adjusted" (default) or "raw". The first one uses the PRS contribution to the evaluation regression model and the second one the R^2 of the full model.

sigTest

How to assess statistical significance between initial PRS R^2 calculations and the respective R^2 (or other prsSelectCrit metrics) from the prisma aggreagated result. One or of "ttest" (default), "wilcoxon" or "empirical". See also Details.

filters

Filters to be applied to the gwe, during the workflow executed in each prisma iteration. For details, see the filterGWAS function.

pcaMethod

Which method to use for PCA. It can be one of "auto" (default), "snprel" for the parallel PCA method implemented in the package SNPRelate, "grid" or "hubert" for robust (but very slow) PCA. See also the gwa function.

imputeMissing

Impute missing values in each prisma iteration? Defaults to TRUE, see also Details.

imputeMethod

One of "single" (default) or "split". See the imputeGWAS for details.

gwaMethods

The GWAS SNP effect estimation method(s) to use in order to estimate the effects that will be used for PRS weights. It can be one or more from "glm", "rrblup", "snptest", "statgen" and "plink". See the gwa function for more details.

gwaCombine

How to combine SNP p-values from more than one GWAS effect estimation methods. Currently not used.

glmOpts

Options list specific to GLM effect estimation. See the gwa function for more details.

rrblupOpts

Options list specific to rrBLUP effect estimation. See the gwa function for more details.

statgenOpts

Options list specific to statgenGWAS effect estimation. See the gwa function for more details.

snptestOpts

Options list specific to SNPTEST effect estimation. See the gwa function for more details.

plinkOpts

Options list specific to PLINK effect estimation. See the gwa function for more details.

prsMethods

One or more PRS extraction algorithms to be included in the prisma workflow. Can be "prcise", "lassosum" or both.

lassosumOpts

Options list specific to lassosum PRS extraction. See the runPRS function for more details.

prsiceOpts

Options list specific to PRSice2 PRS extraction. See the runPRS function for more details.

prsWorkspace

A local directory to be used for prisma operations. Defaults to NULL for auto-generation. See also Details.

cleanup

Cleanup level after the finish of the prisma pipeline. "none" (default) leaves all intermediate output intact. "intermediate" deletes the files produced in effect estimation as well as BED, BIM and FAM files required by PRSice2 and lassosum linkage files. "all" deletes the entire prsWorkspace.

logging

One of "screen" (default) or "file". Where to write log messages. If prisma runs in parallel, it is "file" all the time.

dnOutput

The output of prsPipeline called from this function. Can be "gwaslist" (default) for a list of GWASExperiments or "summaries" for a summary required for next steps of the prisma pipelie. The latter has obviously a smaller size.

output

The level of output of this function. It can be "normal" for a list with the necessary information to create the prisma report or "full" which also contains the itermediate output of prsPipeline called within prisma.

continue

Continue a crashed pipeline? Defaults to FALSE, see Details.

useDenovoWorkspace

Validate the prisma combined PRS in the initial dataset splits or generate new ones. Defaults to NULL, see also Details.

runId

A unique run id for the run. If not given, it will be auto-generated.

evalOnSplit

Which data split to use to evaluate the PRS. "original" (default) uses the original split and SNP effect calculations, while "new" creates a new split taking much more time.

evalWith

How to perform the PRS evaluation regressions. It can be "vanilla" (default) to do it with R or "prsice" to do it with PRSice2. The latter takes much more time as there is intermediate writing of PLINK files.

sitadelaDb

Either NULL or a sitadela SQLite database with at least human RefSeq annotations for hg19 and hg38. It is used to add gene names to PRS SNP loci.

snpSelection

A data frame with candidate SNPs, the output, or part of the output of aggregatePrsMarkers, or one of the list members of the output of selectPrs.

rc

The fraction of available cores to use for parallel calculations. Default is NULL for no parallelization.

...

Arguments passed to prisma from the prismaPipeline wrapper..

retry

The number of pipeline relaunches in case of crash for any reason. Defaults to 10.

outPath

The path to the directory where checkpoint files and the report will be written. It can be different from prsWorkspace and defaults to NULL for auto-generation.

Value

A list with the members params and results. Both are lists. The params member has the following contents:

  • call which contains the function call.

  • args which contains a list of all arguments used, default and user-specific, irrespective of call.

The results member is a named list with length as the vector gweMethods and each sublist corresponds to results for each SNP effect calculation method. Each one of them has the following contents:

  • candidates, a named list of data frames containing the SNPs within each PRS candidate. The names correspond to the number of SNPs in the PRS candidates and the candidates are determined based on prsSelectMethod.

  • iterations which is NULL or the output of each prisma iteration (multiple outputs of prsSelection) if output="full".

  • reportData which is an internal structure containing PRS evaluation metrics and ggplot2 objects used to make the prisma report.

This object can be saved in and .rda file and later used with cross-validation metrics and lookup in the GWAS catalog (prismaLookup function). These three elements are required to build a prisma report (prismaReport function).

Details

Regarding the dnList argument, this is a list of either GWASExperiment objects or a list of lists, each summarizing a GWASExperiment object to save space/memory as not all the elements of a GWASExperiment object are required for downstream analyses. The content of dnList is determined by the output argument of prsPipeline. When the latter is "summaries", dnList sublists have the following members:

  • baseIndex: the sample indices that were used for the extraction of summary statistics via gwa (training).

  • targetIndex: the sample indices that were used for PRS extraction and validation in the supported pipelines (testing).

  • effects: the effects (regression coefficients or odds ratios) for each SNP (summary statistics).

  • prsbetas: a subset of regression coefficients and/or adjusted ones in the case of lassosum, which comprise the PRS weights.

  • npcs: the number of principal components included in the regression model.

  • pr2: a data frame with metrics returned from PRSice2, such as PRS p-value and R^2.

dnList can essentially be the outcome only of a de novo PRS extraction pipeline.

Regarding the trainSize argument, this controls the fraction of the input GWASExperiment object (i.e. the fraction of the input dataset) that will be used for the calculation of summary statistics using the link{gwa} function (usually). These summary statistics are then used with the rest of the samples (fraction 1 - trainSize) for PRS extraction, that is a input to the supported PRS algorithms (PRSice2, lassosum). Therefore, in each prisma iteration (out of niter), trainSize*ncol(gwe) samples are used to calculate summary statistics and (1-trainSize)*ncol(gwe) are used as targets in the PRS extrction process.

Regarding the dropSameQuantiles argument, when resolution="quantile", it is possible that the number of SNPs at different quantiles of the frequency of appearance distribution is the same. By default, the PRS is not evaluated at the highest quantile with the same number of SNPs as the next lower one (dropSameQuantiles=FALSE). For example, if the number of PRS SNPs at Q=0.5 and Q=0.75 is 1000, then there will be no evaluation at Q=0.75. To force such an evaluation, set dropSameQuantiles=TRUE.

Regarding the "aggregation" argument, this controls how should PRS SNP candidates from different PRS algorithms should be consolidated. When "intersection", SNPs included in the PRS suggested by all algorithms synthesize the PRS candidate set. When "union", it is the union of SNPs present in all PRSs. The final SNP set is then used to create a distribution of appearances (frequency of each SNP across "niter" iterations) which is the basis for later selection.

Regarding the effectWeight argument, this controls how the SNP effects in PRS candidates are summarized over niter iterations to produce the final effects for the calculation of weighted PRS. When "mean" (default), the final effect for a SNP is the mean off all its effects across niter iterations, when it appears. When "median", it's the respective median while when "weight", the SNP effects are weighted by 1 minus the recorded PRS R^2 so that the "best" runs can be given more value.

Regarding the prsSelectMethod argument, this controls how the final PRS is selected after the end of niter iterations and based on the requested evaluation metrics (typically the PRS R^2). When "maxima"(default), a distribution of PRS R^2 values is created with the PRS R^2 values (or rarer, other chosen metric) derived from niter iterations. This distribution (if R^2-related) may further be adjusted according to the number of SNPs comrpising in the PRS, according to the prsSelectR2 argument. Then, from this distribution, local maxima are calculated. The local maximum with the highest R^2 is considered the best candidate and provides the number of SNPs. The other maxima are returned also as further candidates. When "elbow" the, elbow point method is used for determining the optimal number of SNPs. The elbow method is a heuristic used in determining the number of features in a data set with respect to some optimization criterion. In this case the criterion is the value of PRS R^2 and the method consists of plotting the PRS explained variation (as depicted by R^2) as a function of the number of SNPs in the PRS.

Regarding the prsSelectCrit argument, this controls the criterion used to select the final PRS after the end of the iterative process and according to the evaluation metrics. When "prs_r2" (default), the decision making plots and the prsSelectMethod operate on the PRS R^2 calculated in each PRS extraction iteration. When "prs_pvalue", the -log_10(PRS p-valye) is used and when "prs_aic", the AIC (Akaike's Information Criterion) is used.

Regarding the sigTest argument, this controls how (any) statistical significance is assessed in the comparison of the initial PRS R^2 calculations (as this is returned by PRSice2) and the PRS R^2 of the prisma combined approach. Essentially, the two PRS R^2 (or full model R^2 as determined by prsSelectCrit) distributions are compared using a t-test (default), a Wilcoxon rank test or an empirical test. In the latter case, the 'p-value' is the number of times that the R^2 of the prisma combination method is smaller than the initial R^2 divided by the number of iterations. The outcome is presented in the prisma report.

Regarding the imputeMissing argument, it is practically not used with a pre-processed dataset which should not contain missing values. If the initial dataset has missing values, imputation will be performed in each step, slowing down the procedure.

Regarding the prsWorkspace argument, this controls where the prisma intermediate files and results as well as configuration files will be stored. If NULL (not recommended!), a temporary directory is used. This directory hosts:

  • a JSON file with run parameters called params.json.

  • one subdirectory for each iteration which contains intermediate files used e.g. by SNPTEST, PLINK, PRSice2 etc. These directories are named based on the runId and the iteration number.

  • log file for each iteration, named similarly as the run subdirectory.

Regarding the continue argument, this can be set to TRUE to continue a crashed pipeline, given the initial gwe argument and the prisma workspace. If the workspace is not found, a new run will be started. Generally, as the prisma pipeline combines several often disjoint components (including several system commands), it is possible that something can go wrong. We have done our best to modularize the pipeline which can be restarted from various automatically detected checkpoints.

Regarding the useDenovoWorkspace argument, if useDenovoWorkspace is a valid prisma workspace or a list output from prsPipeline, the PRS validation is performed using the original data split. If NULL, then a completely new split is generated. The later can take very long time, so it is advised to use an existing split if available. This argument is available in the prsPipeline and prsSelection functions when used directly. When executing the complete pipeline through prisma, this is controlled by the evalOnSplit argument. When the latter is evalOnSplit="original", the workspace generated in prisma initiation is used. When evalOnSplit="new", the initial split is ignored and a new split is created and evaluated, taking much more time as the SNP effect calculation takes place again.

Examples

data(toy,package="prisma")
gdsfile(toy) <- system.file(package="prisma","extdata","toy.gds")

# Lose filters for the toy dataset
filts <- getDefaults("filters")
filts$IBD <- NA
filts$hwe <- 1e-3
filts$pcaOut <- FALSE
filts$inbreed <- NA

# Workspace
d1 <- tempfile()
wspace1 <- file.path(tempdir(),d1)

# Traits
response <- "BMI"
covariates <- c("Case_Control","Gender","Age")

# Complete 4-iteration PRS pipeline - ~1 min to run with 4 cores - no PCA
if (Sys.which("PRSice_linux") != "") {

prismaOut <- prisma(
    gwe=toy,
    phenotype=response,
    covariates=covariates,
    pcs=FALSE,
    trainSize=0.8,
    niter=4,
    resolution="frequency",
    minSnps=2,
    filters=filts,
    pcaMethod="snprel",
    imputeMissing=FALSE,
    gwaMethods=c("glm","statgen"),
    prsiceOpts=list(clump_p=0.75,perm=100),
    prsWorkspace=wspace1,
    cleanup="intermediate",
    logging="file",
    output="normal"#,
    #rc=0.25
)

# Below, individual wrapper steps implemented in prisma as whole
# Output only of the discovery PRS pipeline with statgenGWAS
d2 <- tempfile()
wspace2 <- file.path(tempdir(),d2)
dnList <- prsPipeline(
    gwe=toy,
    phenotype=response,
    covariates=covariates,
    pcs=FALSE,
    trainSize=0.8,
    niter=4,
    filters=filts,
    pcaMethod="snprel",
    imputeMissing=FALSE,
    gwaMethods="statgen",
    prsiceOpts=list(clump_p=0.75,perm=100),
    prsWorkspace=wspace2,
    cleanup="intermediate",
    logging="file"#,
    #rc=0.25
)

# After, calculate the evaluation metrics
d3 <- tempfile()
wspace3 <- file.path(tempdir(),d3)
evalMetrics <- prsSelection(
    dnList=dnList,
    gwe=toy,
    phenotype=response,
    covariates=covariates,
    pcs=FALSE,
    trainSize=0.8,
    niter=4,
    resolution="frequency",
    minSnps=2,
    filters=filts,
    pcaMethod="snprel",
    imputeMissing=FALSE,
    gwaMethods="statgen",
    prsiceOpts=list(clump_p=0.75,perm=100),
    prsWorkspace=wspace3,
    cleanup="intermediate",
    logging="file",
    output="summary",
    useDenovoWorkspace=dnList#,
    #rc=0.25
)

candidates <- selectPrs(
    metrics=evalMetrics$metrics,
    snpSelection=evalMetrics$pgs,
    gwe=toy,
    base=evalMetrics$baseline
)

}
